<br>
I have yet to see ANY form of government work the way it was intended. Human greed will always taint even the noblest intentions.<br>
<br>
Speaking of money... The dollar is merely a form of measurement. If anyone thinks to ask 'a dollar of what?' the correct response is CREDIT (or possibly DEBT, depending on how you look at it). Thank you Fed. :P  The sad thing is some of the highest rated currency in the world has NOTHING backing it.  ... now, how much more is money worth than people?<br>
<br>
Trickle down theory doesn't work. That much has been proven by Everquest. Just look at the high level caster spells. VI said they would 'trickle down' to the lower level people. The problem is greed reared it's ugly head again. Many high level spells have been first distributed to the casters in the uber guilds, then all other copies are either destroyed, sold to other uber guilds or sold to other players for asinine amounts of money. Admittedly this isn't the best example, but I believe it makes my point. Nearly every problem we face today can be traced back to a person or group's greed. <br>
<br>
There is nothing wrong with Capitalism if applied the way it was intended. The intention is to create and SPREAD wealth through trade and work. Not a thing wrong with that... until you add the damning factor that people are involved. There's where it starts to go horribly wrong. Some on the top decide that they want more, so begin to tighten their grip, choking the SPREADING part and hoarding the wealth creation part for themselves.<br>
<br>
There is also nothing wrong with Socialism... until you bring people into the equation. There are just far too many self-serving and just plain greedy (there it is again) people to allow this to flourish. <br>
<br>
Until we as a society (world-wide if necessary) can find an alternative to the necessity for money (for example: free, clean unlimited power) there will always be those that seek to hoard it and at the same time not allow it to fall into the hands of others.<br>
<br>
<br>
Being in EQ has actually shown me a large number of social aspects reflected from the real world that I probably wouldn't have ever seen. This game (or as I like to call it, experience) tends to amplify human nature and really show what they are like. It seems being online and protected by anonymity actually AMPLIFIES someone's personality.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The world can be unequally wealthy, or it can be equally poor. Being equally wealthy is not an option.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
This illustrates my point. Why does wealth matter that much? If you're willing to put in some work, you don't actually need ANY money at all. Admittedly, that would basically make you a farmer, but then again isn't it food we're REALLY all working for anyway? I don't know many people that could survive with no food at all. I know I could survive without my computer... for a while anyway. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
